The paper discusses a real-time motion planning framework for robots to function autonomously in dynamic environments, which involves intention inference by reasoning counterfactually about potential motion of other agents. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the Robotics (cs.RO) and Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) sub-categories. The paper also mentions a distributed visual tracking method, which implies that it may also belong to the Computer Vision (cs.CV) sub-category. The paper further discusses a novel approach that represents a computationally efficient alternative to previously studied policy learning methods, which suggests that it may also belong to the Machine Learning (cs.LG) sub-category. Finally, the paper deals with multi-robot and human-robot navigation, which implies that it may also belong to the Systems and Control (cs.SY) sub-category.
